article.headline: California 43, Washington State 41
article.story: PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- Pac-10 scoring leader Leon Powe recorded 21 points Thursday night, but California's gifted sophomore was the first to admit that his points did not come easy. "To tell you the truth, I don't like playing this team," Powe said after the Golden Bears edged the Washington State Cougars 43-41. "They give me headaches." Powe was referring to Washington State's tenacious defense and patient offense. The 43 points was a season low for California (17-7, 14-4 Pac-10) and the lowest Bears total in a win since 1985. Derrick Low led Washington State (11-13, 4-11) with just eight points. WSU's Robbie Cowgill drew contact with a California defender and missed badly on a runner in the lane just before the final horn. "It might have been (a foul), it might have not," Cowgill said. "It's not for me to say." "If I was a ref, I wouldn't have called it," Powe said. Powe scored 13 of California's 19 points in the second half, including 11 of the first 13. "If I hadn't been aggressive (in the second half), I don't know what score we would have had up there. It was just an ugly game," Powe said. "It was one of the ugliest games I've been in. It just feels like everything is in slow motion." In the second half, California shot 33 percent from the field, missed all 10 3-point attempts and blew 7 of 10 free throws. For the game, California shot 40 percent from the field and held Washington State to 38 percent. "They are tough defensively," California coach Ben Braun said. "They always have been. (WSU coach) Dick Bennett is at the genius level defensively." The Cougars, who rank among the national leaders with 57.4 points allowed per game, are 0-4 in two-point games in the Pac-10 this season. The Bears, who beat WSU 55-53 on Jan. 28, are 6-1 in Pac-10 games decided by four points or less. "We deserve to win a few of these games," Cowgill said. "It's obviously frustrating." Each team scored just two points -- on one field goal each -- in the first six minutes. California snapped a 12-12 tie midway through the first half with a 10-0 run and led 24-19 after Ayinde Ubaka scored 12 of his 14 points in the first half. Washington State never led after 5-4, but the Cougars forged a 39-all tie on Caleb Forrest's jump shot with 2:50 left. Rod Benson soon answered with a rebound basket to push California ahead to stay. The Bears have won seven of eight overall and 11 of the last 13 meetings with Washington State. The Cougars have lost three in a row overall and three in a row to California.
